It is unstable.

00:37:38.128 --> 00:37:42.431
The system wants to relax.
It wants to relax to a lower

00:37:42.431 --> 00:37:45.061
energy state.
And when it does so,

00:37:45.061 --> 00:37:48.249
because it's going to lower
energy state,

00:37:48.249 --> 00:37:52.632
it has to emit radiation.
And that radiation is going to

00:37:52.632 --> 00:37:56.935
come out as a photon whose
energy is exactly the energy

00:37:56.935 --> 00:38:01.000
difference between these two
states.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:05.109
That's the quantum nature,
here, of the hydrogen atom.

00:38:05.109 --> 00:38:08.754
The photon that comes out has
to have an energy,

00:38:08.754 --> 00:38:13.096
delta E, which is exactly the
energy of the initial state

00:38:13.096 --> 00:38:16.585
minus that of the final state.
And, therefore,

00:38:16.585 --> 00:38:21.470
the frequency of that radiation
is going to have one value given

00:38:21.470 --> 00:38:25.812
by this energy difference
divided by Planck's constant h.

00:38:25.812 --> 00:38:30.000
That is what's happening in the
discharge.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:34.009
What we've got is some hydrogen
atoms excited to say,

00:38:34.009 --> 00:38:35.937
for example,
this B state,

00:38:35.937 --> 00:38:40.641
which is a lower energy state,
and so when it relaxes there is

00:38:40.641 --> 00:38:44.728
a small energy difference
between here and this bottom

00:38:44.728 --> 00:38:47.273
state.
Therefore, you are going to

00:38:47.273 --> 00:38:49.818
have a low frequency of
radiation.

00:38:49.818 --> 00:38:54.599
If you have some other hydrogen
atoms in the discharge that are

00:38:54.599 --> 00:38:58.917
excited to this state up here,
well, this is a big energy

00:38:58.917 --> 00:39:02.915
difference.
And so delta E is going to be

00:39:02.915 --> 00:39:04.301
large.
And, therefore,

00:39:04.301 --> 00:39:07.867
you're going to have some
radiation emitted that's at a

00:39:07.867 --> 00:39:10.443
high frequency because delta E
is large.

00:39:10.443 --> 00:39:14.009
If it's at a high frequency,
it's going to have a short

00:39:14.009 --> 00:39:16.716
wavelength.
These hydrogen atoms are going

00:39:16.716 --> 00:39:18.830
to have a low frequency
emission.

00:39:18.830 --> 00:39:21.075
It's going to be a long
wavelength.

00:39:21.075 --> 00:39:24.773
So, we've got a mixture of
atoms in this state or in this

00:39:24.773 --> 00:39:29.000
state or in any other states in
this discharge.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:32.549
Now, let's try to understand
this spectrum.

00:39:32.549 --> 00:39:37.450
And to do that I have drawn an
energy level diagram for the

00:39:37.450 --> 00:39:40.746
hydrogen atom.
Here is n equals 1 state,

00:39:40.746 --> 00:39:45.309
n equals 2, n equals 3,
n equals 4, all the way up to n

00:39:45.309 --> 00:39:49.619
equals 0 here on the top.
They get closer and closer

00:39:49.619 --> 00:39:52.830
together as we go up.
This purple line,

00:39:52.830 --> 00:39:56.464
it turns out,
or the purple color comes from

00:39:56.464 --> 00:40:01.112
a transition made from a
hydrogen atom in the n equals 6

00:40:01.112 --> 00:40:07.022
state to the n equals 2 state.
The final n here is 2.

00:40:07.022 --> 00:40:12.077
The blue line comes from a
hydrogen atom that has made a

00:40:12.077 --> 00:40:16.213
transition from n equals 5 also
to n equals 2.

00:40:16.213 --> 00:40:20.808
The green line is from a
hydrogen atom that makes a

00:40:20.808 --> 00:40:26.415
transition from n equals 4 to n
equals 2 and then the red line

00:40:26.415 --> 00:40:32.576
from n equals 3 to n equals 2.
Of course, the transition from

00:40:32.576 --> 00:40:36.613
n equals 3 to n equals 2 is the
smallest energy.

00:40:36.613 --> 00:40:40.993
Therefore, it is going to be
the longest wavelength.

00:40:40.993 --> 00:40:44.343
n equals 6 to n equals 2
largest energy.

00:40:44.343 --> 00:40:48.981
Therefore, it is going to have
the smallest wavelength.

00:40:48.981 --> 00:40:53.877
Now, how do we know that these
frequencies agree with what

00:40:53.877 --> 00:40:58.000
Schrödinger predicted they
should be?

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:01.434
Well, to know that,
what we're going to do is we're

00:41:01.434 --> 00:41:04.044
going to write down this
equation here,

00:41:04.044 --> 00:41:08.096
which is just telling us what
the frequency of the radiation

00:41:08.096 --> 00:41:12.080
should be, it is delta E over H.
But we're going to use the

00:41:12.080 --> 00:41:16.476
predictions from the Schrödinger
equation and plug them into here

00:41:16.476 --> 00:41:19.292
to calculate what the frequency
should be.

00:41:19.292 --> 00:41:22.933
We were told here that the
energy, say, of the initial

00:41:22.933 --> 00:41:27.054
state given by the Schrödinger
equation is minus R sub H over

00:41:27.054 --> 00:41:29.389
the initial quantum number
squared.

00:41:29.389 --> 00:41:34.009
We're going to plug that into

00:41:34.009 --> 00:41:35.534
there.
The final state,

00:41:35.534 --> 00:41:38.792
well, that's also the
expression for the energy,

00:41:38.792 --> 00:41:41.217
we're going to plug that into
there.

00:41:41.217 --> 00:41:44.198
We're then going to rearrange
that equation,

00:41:44.198 --> 00:41:48.287
so we get the frequency is the
Rydberg constant over H times

00:41:48.287 --> 00:41:52.237
this quantity (1 over n sub f
squared minus 1 over n sub i

00:41:52.237 --> 00:41:54.524
squared).

00:41:54.524 --> 00:42:00.000
And since I told you
here that all of these lines --

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:04.090
The final quantum number is 2.
We can plug that in.

00:42:04.090 --> 00:42:07.772
And then we can just go in and
put in 3, 4, 5,

00:42:07.772 --> 00:42:12.190
6 and get predictions for what
nu is for the frequency.

00:42:12.190 --> 00:42:17.018
And what you would find is that
predictions that this makes,

00:42:17.018 --> 00:42:22.009
the Schrödinger equation makes
agrees with the observations of

00:42:22.009 --> 00:42:27.000
the frequencies of these lines
to one part in 10^8.

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:32.638
There is really just remarkable
agreement between the energies

00:42:32.638 --> 00:42:38.369
or the frequencies predicted by
Schršdinger's equation and what

00:42:38.369 --> 00:42:41.974
we actual observe for the
hydrogen atom.

00:42:41.974 --> 00:42:47.613
Here is another diagram of the
energies of the hydrogen atom n

00:42:47.613 --> 00:42:50.571
equals 1, n equals 2,
n equals 3.

00:42:50.571 --> 00:42:56.025
And the four lines that we were
looking at where shown right

00:42:56.025 --> 00:43:00.000
here.
These are the four lines.

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:04.980
Here is n equals 6 to n equals
2, n equals 5 to n equals 2.

00:43:04.980 --> 00:43:09.188
These lines are actually called
the Balmer series.

00:43:09.188 --> 00:43:13.997
I want you to know that there
is also a transition from n

00:43:13.997 --> 00:43:17.346
equals 6 to n equals 1.
It is over here.

00:43:17.346 --> 00:43:22.240
But you can see that that
transition is a very high energy

00:43:22.240 --> 00:43:25.675
transition.
That transition occurs in the

00:43:25.675 --> 00:43:31.000
ultraviolet range of the
electromagnetic spectrum.

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:33.433
And, therefore,
you cannot see it,

00:43:33.433 --> 00:43:36.751
but it is there.
Actually, what you can see is

00:43:36.751 --> 00:43:41.175
that there are transitions from
these higher energy states to

00:43:41.175 --> 00:43:44.714
the ground state,
transitions from all of them to

00:43:44.714 --> 00:43:47.589
the ground state,
but they're all in the

00:43:47.589 --> 00:43:51.202
ultraviolet range of the
electromagnetic spectrum.

00:43:51.202 --> 00:43:54.225
That is why you cannot see that
right now.

00:43:54.225 --> 00:43:57.396
But those lines are called the
Lyman series.

00:43:57.396 --> 00:44:03.000
And then there are transitions
here to the n equals 3 state.

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:07.863
These transitions from the
larger quantum number to n

00:44:07.863 --> 00:44:11.417
equals 3 are called the Paschen
series.

00:44:11.417 --> 00:44:14.316
They occur in the near
infrared.

00:44:14.316 --> 00:44:17.215
Brackett series in the
infrared.

00:44:17.215 --> 00:44:20.208
Pfund series in the far
infrared.

00:44:20.208 --> 00:44:24.978
I got that backwards.
And these different series are

00:44:24.978 --> 00:44:30.990
all labeled by the final state.
And they're labeled by the

00:44:30.990 --> 00:44:34.970
names of the discoverers.
And the reason there are so

00:44:34.970 --> 00:44:39.256
many different discoverers is
because in order to see the

00:44:39.256 --> 00:44:43.619
different kinds of radiation,
you have to have a different

00:44:43.619 --> 00:44:47.217
kind of detector.
And, depending on what kind of

00:44:47.217 --> 00:44:51.580
a detector an experimentalist
had, well, that will dictate

00:44:51.580 --> 00:44:55.637
then what he actually can see,
what kind of radiation,

00:44:55.637 --> 00:45:00.000
which ones of these transitions
he can view.

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:04.858
Now, we looked at emission.
But it is also possible for

00:45:04.858 --> 00:45:09.807
there to be absorption between
these allowed states of a

00:45:09.807 --> 00:45:13.856
hydrogen atom.
That is, we can have a hydrogen

00:45:13.856 --> 00:45:18.984
atom here in a low energy state,
the initial state E sub i.

00:45:18.984 --> 00:45:22.403
And if there is a photon around

00:45:22.403 --> 00:45:27.712
whose energy matches the energy
difference between these two

00:45:27.712 --> 00:45:31.041
states, well,
then, that photon can be

00:45:31.041 --> 00:45:36.832
absorbed by the hydrogen atom.
Again, the energy of that

00:45:36.832 --> 00:45:40.938
photon has to be exactly the
difference in energy between

00:45:40.938 --> 00:45:44.310
those two states.
It cannot be a little larger.

00:45:44.310 --> 00:45:48.343
If it is a little larger,
that photon is not going to be

00:45:48.343 --> 00:45:50.249
absorbed.
That's important.

00:45:50.249 --> 00:45:54.208
That's the quantum nature,
again, of the hydrogen atom.

00:45:54.208 --> 00:45:58.460
There are specific energies
that are allowed and nothing in

00:45:58.460 --> 00:46:02.071
between.
And then, from knowing the

00:46:02.071 --> 00:46:05.895
energy of the photon,
you can get that frequency.

00:46:05.895 --> 00:46:10.118
And then in the case of
absorption, the frequencies of

00:46:10.118 --> 00:46:14.579
the radiation that can be
absorbed by a hydrogen atom are

00:46:14.579 --> 00:46:18.802
given by this expression.
This expression differs from

00:46:18.802 --> 00:46:23.582
the frequencies for emission
only in that I've reversed these

00:46:23.582 --> 00:46:26.769
two terms.
This is 1 over n sub i squared.

00:46:26.769 --> 00:46:31.943
This is 1 over n sub f squared.

00:46:31.943 --> 00:46:36.161
I have reversed them so that

00:46:36.161 --> 00:46:41.556
you come out with a frequency
that is a positive number.

00:46:41.556 --> 00:46:44.892
Frequencies do have to be
positive.

00:46:44.892 --> 00:46:49.895
So, we've got two different
expressions here for the

00:46:49.895 --> 00:46:55.487
frequency depending on whether
we're absorbing a photon or

00:46:55.487 --> 00:47:00.000
we're emitting a photon.
